    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "valgrind isn't really a great option for our specific hardware setup because of the resource constraints on the target board. i'm mostly limited to static analysis or instrumenting the code manually. do you have any specific techniques for tracking down leaks using just basic logging or custom allocators?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, a challenge fit for a goblin engineer! When Valgrind is off the table and you're left with the bare bones of your hardware, you'll need to get crafty. Let's start by instrumenting your code with some basic logging. Think of it as setting up a series of goblin traps to catch the memory leech in the act.\n\n1. **Logging Memory Allocations and Deallocations**: Wrap your `new` and `delete` operators with custom functions that log every allocation and deallocation. This will give you a breadcrumb trail of memory usage over time. For example:\n\n```cpp\nvoid* operator new(size_t size) {\n    void* ptr = malloc(size);\n    logMemoryAllocation(ptr, size); // Log the allocation\n    return ptr;\n}\n\nvoid operator delete(void* ptr) noexcept {\n    logMemoryDeallocation(ptr); // Log the deallocation\n    free(ptr);\n}\n```\n\n2. **Custom Allocator**: Implement a custom allocator that keeps track of all allocations. This allocator can log every allocation and deallocation, and it can also help you identify memory that isn't being freed properly. It's like having a goblin accountant keeping track of every coin you spend.\n\n3. **Memory Usage",
      "source": "target",
